post_text:
Our schools will soon be hosting on-campus “Meet the Teacher/Orientation” events, specifically for students in transition years – Pre-K, kindergarten, 6th grade, and 9th grade. The in-person events will take place on the following dates:

Thursday, August 13, or Wednesday, August 19, for 6th grade and 9th grade
Thursday, August 20, for Pre-K and kindergarten
Schools will communicate their plans and schedules for students in all other grade levels. Please check your school’s website for more details. New families should contact schools to virtually enroll or to arrange an on-site appointment.

We encourage all families to complete the enrollment process now in an effort to be ready for the start of the school year.

Thank you.

post_text:
All Pasco Schools 12-month employees,

Due to an error by the payroll processor, direct deposit paychecks for 12-month employees have been delayed.

The payroll processor has reassured us that the paychecks will be posted by 5 p.m. today (Friday).

The school district forwarded the payroll files on time this week. Unfortunately, the payroll processor delayed processing the files, and has now acknowledged the error and is confident the problem has been fixed.

Sorry for the inconvenience.

post_text:
Another Farm Fresh Pop Up? You bet.

Tomorrow, Friday, June 12, we will be handing out variety boxes on a drive-thru basis at Chasco Middle School. Each box will include fruits and vegetables, as well as cheese, butter, milk, and diced chicken.

Chasco Middle is at 7702 Ridge Road in Port Richey.

The trucks are expected to arrive at the locations at approximately 8:30 a.m. Distribution will start as soon as the crews set up the delivery stations, and will continue until the boxes run out. We will practice safe social distancing and wear masks. We ask that members of the public remain in their vehicles. Just pop the trunk and we’ll do the rest.

Pasco County Schools
June 10 at 2:16 PM ·

Our next Farm Fresh Pop-Up is tomorrow!

On Thursday, June 11, we will be handing out variety boxes of fruits, vegetables, dairy, and chicken on a drive-thru basis at two locations. Each box will include fruits and vegetables, as well as cheese, butter, milk, and diced chicken.

The Farm Fresh Pop Up events are intended to help families who are struggling to put food on the table. The school district continues to work with local farmers who are willing to donate fresh fruits and vegetables to help the community.

The locations are:
• Fivay High School at 12115 Chicago Avenue in Hudson
• Wesley Chapel High School at 30651 Wells Road in
Wesley Chapel

The trucks are expected to arrive at the locations at approximately 8:30 a.m. Distribution will start as soon as the crews set up the delivery stations, and will continue until the boxes run out. We will practice safe social distancing and wear masks. We ask that members of the public remain in their vehicles. Just pop the trunk and we’ll do the rest.

Our next Farm Fresh Pop Up is tomorrow!
On Friday, June 5, we will be handing out variety boxes of fruits, vegetables, dairy, and diced chicken on a drive-thru basis at three separate locations:
• Fivay High School at 12115 Chicago Avenue in Hudson
• Centennial Middle School at 38505 Centennial Road in

• Wesley Chapel High School at 30651 Wells Road in

The Farm Fresh Pop Up events are intended to help families who are struggling to put food on the table. The school district continues to work with local farmers who are generously donating food of all kinds to help the community. In this case, the variety boxes are being provided by Farm Share.

post_text:
Congratulations to Anna Speer, a junior from Wiregrass Ranch High School. Her oil painting, "Reflections," has been selected as the 2020 winner of the Congressional Art Competition, which recognizes and encourages artistic talent among high school students in Florida's Twelfth Congressional District.
Anna's painting will hang in the U.S. Capitol over the next year. The 2020 award winners are:

First Place: Anna Speer of Wiregrass Ranch HS. Nomination Teacher: Paula Roush-Smith

Award of Merit: Nathan Wang of Land O’Lakes HS. Nominating teacher: Matthew Paltoo

Honorable Mentions: Sarah Evans, Kara Galley, and Kiley Gambrel-Groover of J.W. Mitchell HS. Nominating teacher for each: Donna Fulton

SUMMER FEEDING STARTS THIS WEEK
Beginning tomorrow (Tuesday, June 2) the school district student feeding program will transition to the summer feeding schedule. It includes 25 drive-thru feeding sites and 10 school bus stop sites. The drive-thru sites and the bus deliveries will take place on Tuesday only. However, the food provided will include a lunch and breakfast for five days for each student.
Please review the list of summer drive-thru feeding sites and bus stops offering food for the times and locations: http://www.pasco.k12.fl.us/coronavirus/page/feeding-students

Our very own Chef Blythe from Wiregrass Ranch High School's Hospitality Industry program has you covered with his LOADED Turkey Burger Cups recipe! These cups are juicy and delicious and also Keto and gluten friendly. Check out the recipe here:

Bacon, cooked 8 slices
Ground turkey 2lbs
Chives 4 each
Black pepper To taste
Kosher salt To taste
Cheddar Jack cheese 2 1/2 cups
Bread and butter pickles
Ranch dressing

post_text: Pasco Curbing Hunger Food Drive at Wesley Chapel Sam’s Club
text: Pasco Curbing Hunger Food Drive at Wesley Chapel Sam’s Club

post_text:
The Pasco Curbing Hunger Food Drive is happening today. Location- Sam’s Club of Wesley Chapel at 27727 SR 56, from 8 a.m. until 3 p.m.

We’re looking for non-perishable items – make-a-meal items such as canned goods, rice, pasta, and instant potatoes; as well as healthy snacks such as peanut butter, jelly, crackers, cereal, and granola bars. We will be practicing social distancing, so just place your donated items in a box or bag, and place it in your trunk. Pop open your trunk when you arrive. We’ll do the rest.

You can also make a monetary donation. Just go to www.PascoEducationFoundation.org , click on Donate Now! and specify that your donation is for the Pasco Curbing Hunger Drive. 100 percent of the proceeds will go to feed needy families in Pasco County.

post_text:
Following the successful food drive on May 2, Pasco County leaders are joining together to support a second curbside food drive this Saturday to benefit needy families in Pasco County.

The food drive will occur on Saturday, May 9, at Sam’s Club of Wesley Chapel at 27727 SR 56, from 8 a.m. until 3 p.m.

The goal is to collect non-perishable items – make-a-meal items such as canned goods, rice, pasta, and instant potatoes; as well as healthy snacks such as peanut butter, jelly, crackers, cereal, and granola bars.

Volunteers at the collection sites will be practicing social distancing and wearing masks. Members of the public will be encouraged to remain in their vehicles. They should place donated items in a box or bag, and place it in their trunk. When they arrive at the donation site, they will be directed to pop open their trunk and volunteers will do the rest.

The food drive also will accept monetary donations through the Pasco Education Foundation at www.PascoEducationFoundation.org. 100 percent of the proceeds will go to feed needy families in Pasco County.

Charles S. Rushe Middle School theatre students recorded this amazing video to cheer up their director Mr. Roush when they realized they would not be to perform their 8th grade musical, You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown.

Here is their message to Mr. Roush. We all love you and we love this show, and we are not giving up either of them. Thank you, Mr. Roush, for being our director and our mentor. You have given joy to every one of your actors. We are your children and the theatre is our family. Sure we may grow up but we will always be in your heart as well as you in ours.

Kindergarten registration is now on Wednesday, July 8 at all of our elementary schools.

Kindergarten Registration Requirements
5 years of age by September 1, 2020
Birth Certificate or other proof of birthdate
Health Examination - HRS Form 3040
HRS Certificate of Immunization
3 different proofs of residency including deed or property tax assessment or lease, current utility bill, and an additional document supporting stated address: auto registration, driver’s license, voter registration.

Please visit this website to pre-register. https://www.pasco.k12.fl.us/forms/view.php?id=227457

post_text:
AP Exam Update
We have received important updates from College Board on AP Exam dates and format.
Exams will be given May from May 11 – 22, with. Make up days offered June 1-5.

View the full testing schedule. https://apcoronavirusupdates.collegeboard.org/educators/taking-the-exams/ap-exam-schedule

Students will be able to take exams on any device they have access to—computer, tablet, or smartphone. They'll be able to type and upload their responses or write responses by hand and submit a photo via their cell phones.
For most subjects, the exams will be 45 minutes long, plus an additional 5 minutes for uploading. Students will need to access the online testing system 30 minutes early to get set up.
For more information visit: https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/about-ap/news-changes/coronavirus-update

Visit this site to enroll in a webinar. https://globalmeet.webcasts.com/starthere.jsp?ei=1302024&tp_key=73070ccd21&SFMC_cid=EM297098-&rid=30060756

post_text:
Focus for the Week from the new edition of our Parent Newsletter.

We recognize that this learning situation is new for the majority of our students in Pasco and that many families are also facing unprecedented circumstances with your own work routines and lives. It is incredibly important that you know we all support you in balancing Distance Learning with your current circumstances. If it feels like too much for you or your students, adjust to what is manageable and we will work to support you. If it feels like it is not enough, please feel free to have your students work on any number of the supplemental resources available to them on myPascoConnect.

We are here for you, we understand that each student and family is different and that what works for some may not work for others and what works for you today may be different tomorrow. It is all okay, we will work through it. Teachers, leaders, and other school staff are available to help and support and we want your students to feel success, please reach out to them if you are in need of help.

post_text:
A few things to know for the start of distance learning tomorrow.
1. Students do not login to MyPascoConnect/MyLearning at a certain time. Work can be done at any time during the day. Please make sure students login and do work each day.
2. High school and middle school students will only see their core classes tomorrow. Electives will not begin for HS and MS until Monday, April 6.
3. Patience. Please have patience for teachers, students, technology, and yourselves. Not everything will be perfect, but if we all work together we can make this a positive experience.
4. We are all here for one thing, the students of Pasco County Schools!

post_text: An update from Superintendent Browning. All Pasco County schools will be closed through May 1. Distance learning begins Tuesday, March 31.
text: An update from Superintendent Browning. All Pasco County schools will be closed through May 1. Distance learning begins Tuesday, March 31.

post_text:
The Florida Commissioner of Education has recommended that schools throughout our state will remain closed through May 1. We are following his recommendation. The roughly two-week extension does not change our current efforts here in Pasco County.

Distance Learning starts tomorrow (Tuesday, March 31) as planned, and we will continue to provide breakfast and lunch to our students free of charge.

We understand the hardship that this causes for families. We will continue to do everything we can to reduce the impact on you and your family.

post_text:
Update. Hudson High School has been added to the Drive Thru Sites.

Here is an update to our feeding plans.

Drive Thru Student Feeding Sites
On Tuesday, March 31, Pasco County Schools will expand the number of student feeding sites to 25. The feeding sites will be activated on Tuesdays only, from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. The bags of food will include breakfast and lunch for five days for each student. The student(s) must be present to receive food.

Food Buses Feeding Pasco Students
On Tuesday, March 31, Pasco County School buses will deliver food to families at 16 bus stops throughout the county. The bus is scheduled for approximately 10 minutes at each bus stop. The bags of food will include breakfast and lunch for five days for each student. The school bus food deliveries are on Tuesdays only. The student(s) must be present to receive food.

post_text:
Thank you to whoever wrote this!

Please offer grace to your child’s teacher and other school personnel. I promise, that educating your children is still our priority. ❤️

March 31st starts a new chapter in public education for schools in Pasco County. There is a huge learning curve that students and teachers will be navigating together!

As we embark on distance learning, I am asking my Facebook friends to refrain from publicly scrutinizing their children’s teachers/schools/district for the way they are teaching or the lessons they are assigning.

We are about to navigate unchartered waters with little, to no prep time. This is a crisis, not a time to be playing armchair quarterback. We love your kids and, we will be doing our absolute best!

🤍💻📝📌📎🖊📓📚🧮➗🖍➕

Please copy & paste if you are a teacher!

And fellow educators, you got this. I believe in you! -author of post unknown

post_text:
We have received important updates from College Board on AP Exams.
Traditional face-to-face exam administrations will not take place.
For the 2019–20 exam administration only, students can take a 45-minute online exam at home. Educator-led development committees are currently selecting the exam questions that will be administered.
Pasco County Schools will keep families updated about testing dates when they are released on April 3rd and will ensure proper planning for students to be informed on when and how to test.
For more information visit: https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/about-ap/news-changes/coronavirus-update

International Baccalaureate will be releasing their information on exam administration by March 27th. Cambridge is also continuing to work through their exam administration and we will keep you updated as we learn more.

Governor DeSantis and the Florida Department of Education have outlined new recommendations for schools. Governor DeSantis has closed all Florida schools, including Pasco County Schools, until April 15. All K-12 state testing has also been canceled.

The previously announced feeding program will still begin as planned on Monday, March 23. There is also a plan to activate our summer feeding buses beginning on Monday, March 30 to deliver more food to students in need throughout Pasco.

The Friday, March 27 training for teachers regarding distance learning will now take place virtually instead of in person. More details to follow.

There is a plan in place to implement distance learning for students on Tuesday, March 31. More information regarding checking out devices for students in need will follow.

PLACE will remain closed until April 15.

More details and information will be shared as it becomes available.

post_text:
Staff in the Spotlight with Valarie Hartley

What is your role in Pasco County?

I am the second grade team leader/ facilitator at Chasco Elementary School.

What do you love about your job?

I love watching the students build their confidence and self-worth. They change their mindset from “I can’t” to “I will.”

Who or what inspires you?

My mother has always been my source of strength and perseverance. She has shown me it is not about how many times you fall but rather about how many times you get back up.

Tell us something unique that people may not know about you.

I have quite the eclectic range of hobbies from fishing, to theatre and everything in between.

The person who nominated Ms. Hartley shared, “She is one of the hardest working teachers I have ever met!”‬‬‬

The District School Board of Pasco County has chosen Kirkland Ranch Academy of Innovation as the name of a new high school focused on technology, STEM, and business programs scheduled to open in August 2022.

The school is located at Curley Road and Keifer Road in Wesley Chapel on the former Kirkland Ranch property. Program plans for the school include academies for Business, Finance & Marketing; Digital Technology; Engineering Technology; Health Science & Human Services; Transportation Technology; and Building Technology. It will serve grades 9 through 12 and offer industry certification in high-demand career fields with a focus on technology, STEM, and business.

post_text:
UPDATE: Happy to report that buses have delivered all students safely home and no buses were toppled by winds.

ORIGINAL MESSAGE:
We have spoken to Pasco County Emergency Operations Director Andy Fossa, who has advised us that sustained winds from 25 to 35 MPH, with gusts as high as 45 MPH, are expected between 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Although we are not dismissing early, staff has decided that we should contact parents and tell them that we aren’t changing anything, but they may check their children out of school early if they are concerned about the weather. Communications will send out a district-wide message to parents.

Buses will operate on their normal schedules. We are in communication with Transportation and drivers will be advised to pull off the road and contact dispatch if they become concerned about weather conditions.

The district is not cancelling evening events at schools, but school leaders may make individual decisions based on their best judgment.

February is Career and Technical Education (CTE) Month. Career and Technical Education provides students access to high-quality, rigorous career-focused programs and offers the academic, technical and employability skills needed for post-secondary and workplace success.

While in school, students have the opportunity to earn industry-recognized certifications and earn college credit through CTE Career Pathways.

Students, talk to your school counselor about enrolling in a CTE class. CTE will assist you in acquiring critical skills in order to jump start your future career through occupational skills training while in high school. For more information visit http://www.pasco.k12.fl.us/cte

post_text:
Staff in the Spotlight: Kim Hinson, Fox Hollow Elementary

What is your role in Pasco County?
I am a first grade teacher and team facilitator at Fox Hollow Elementary.

What do you love about your job?
I love my school family and love seeing my students every morning. My students amaze me every day with their enthusiasm for learning!

Who or what inspires you?
My own daughters inspire me to do my best every day. Cassidy, Mikayla and Sydnee have taught me what it truly means to be a great mom and educator!

Tell us something unique that people may not know about you.
My classroom theme is llamas. I picked that theme for the calming colors. I was not really a llama fan. Over the past two years, my classroom has been filled with llama everything! I am so crazy about them now, they have invaded my home too!

post_text:
Staff in the Spotlight with Jamie Lopey

What is your role in Pasco County?

I am the Plant Manager at Lacoochee Elementary School.

What do you love about your job?

I love the little smiles, high fives, and" Mr. Lopey" hugs from the students. At Lacoochee we are a family!

Who or what inspires you?

My family inspires me! I am a former student of Lacoochee Elementary School. Dr. Renee Sedlack, former LES principal, has always inspired me to be the person I am today. My grandmother, who drove a school bus for thirty years, always pushed me to never give up and focus on my personal goals.

Tell us something unique that people may not know about you.

What people don't know about me is that I have a dream to create a Fishermen mentorship program for children.

The person who nominated Mr. Lopey shared, “He has great relationships with the students and knows each one by name.”
